		<item>
		<title>Who or What?</title>
		<link>https://llgt.cafe/who-or-what</link>
					<comments>https://llgt.cafe/who-or-what#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[llgt]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 29 Apr 2023 16:03:16 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Career]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[LLGT]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://llgt.cafe/?p=768</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[“It’s not what you know, but who you know.” I’m sure that these words have been uttered more than once, but is it true? Honestly, of all the jobs that I’ve worked, I can only think of one job that I had where this might&#160;<a class="read-more" href="https://llgt.cafe/who-or-what">&#8230;</a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>“It’s not what you know, but who you know.” I’m sure that these words have been uttered more than once, but is it true?</p>



<p>Honestly, of all the jobs that I’ve worked, I can only think of one job that I had where this might have applied. It was a part time job and the person who hired me and I had worked together before. But was it really because of who I know or who knew me and what she knew about me.</p>



<p>Yes, there are going to be times when a person is going to get a job just because of the person that he knows, but that probably doesn’t happen very often. That friend of mine who gave me a job probably wouldn’t have given me the job if she thought that I was always going to be late, called in a lot or didn’t work very hard.</p>



<p>How did I get most of my jobs? I took a chance. I put in my application and/or resume and interviewed like anyone else. At the same time, those who hired me took the same chance hiring me. Wherever I work, I always try to do my best and, if my best is good enough, then the employer keeps me. If not, or if I’m not happy with the job, I move on and try something else.</p>



<p>It is through hard work and determination that most people succeed. But success isn’t measured solely by the amount of money that someone is bringing in. Success is also measured by our contribution to the world around us and the enjoyment that we get out of doing the work that we are doing. It is easy enough to find people who hate their jobs who won’t do something else because they need the money. To me, this is just being lazy because these people aren’t willing to look for work that they might actually enjoy. Either that, or these people would be miserable no matter what they did.</p>



<p>Whether we work for someone else or have our own business, it’s not who we know but what others know about us. Do others see us as trustworthy, hard working, caring and dependable? Then they will want to do business with us. Do others see us as lazy, uncaring or undependable? Then they are much less likely to want to associate with us.</p>



<p>If someone tells you that you need to work on something, don’t react negatively to it. Take advise as being helpful, because that’s what it usually is. Yes, there will be people who will offer negative criticism, but try not to take it personally. Negative criticism almost always says more about the person doing the criticizing than the one being criticized.</p>



<p>Remember, always do your best, whatever you do. Colossians 3:23 (KJV) says, “ And whatsoever ye do, do it heartily, as to the Lord, and not unto men.” If you always do your best, you are going to feel better about yourself. If you do your best, you are more likely to succeed. That’s what matters most.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://llgt.cafe/who-or-what/feed</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Serving Others</title>
		<link>https://llgt.cafe/serving-others</link>
					<comments>https://llgt.cafe/serving-others#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[llgt]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 25 Apr 2023 17:10:21 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Career]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[LLGT]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://llgt.cafe/?p=756</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[What’s it like being a chef? I can’t say that I really know. I tried being a sous chef for a while, but it didn’t work out very well. The closest I’ve come was when during the five years that I ran a small soup&#160;<a class="read-more" href="https://llgt.cafe/serving-others">&#8230;</a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>What’s it like being a chef? I can’t say that I really know. I tried being a sous chef for a while, but it didn’t work out very well. The closest I’ve come was when during the five years that I ran a small soup kitchen in northern Idaho, one day a week except for major holidays. During that time, I planned the menu, purchased the groceries or used what was donated to make a meal, along with the two or more others who volunteered their time. Mostly, it was pretty laid back and the main objective, besides bringing glory to God, was to create a good meal for those who stopped by.</p>



<p>Normally, a chef’s main job is to direct his staff and create meals that customers are eager to come back for again and again, and to make money. The more money a restaurant can make, the better chance it has to stay around. There is a fine balance between spending on the ingredients and the amount of money that is taken in. And a small percentage in the profit, either way, can mean the difference between success and a restaurant closing it’s doors for good.</p>



<p>In my work in the soup kitchen, the budget was very limited. I had the money that was donated, any food that was donated, and a small amount of money from the church where the meals were served.</p>



<p>Most restaurants don’t allow for much creativity. There might be one item on a menu that changes from day to day if there is something that needs to be used, or if there is a special purchase. Most restaurants have the same menu day after day. New items are rarely added to most menus and they are usually dropped if the profit margin is too low to keep that item, even if it is a popular item.</p>



<p>A friend observed that just after Christmas, a lot of fast food restraints come out with their own version of a chicken sandwich. There is a certain amount of competition in the restaurant business, though many of the fast food restaurants are owned by the same company.</p>



<p>Hiring and keeping a staff is one of the major issues in the services industry. When I was in cooking school, I had heard that the turnover rate was as high as 300%. During my time in the soup kitchen, I had the same two people helping me in the kitchen the whole time. We did have others who helped. One of the men who helped had a niece who would help and there were others.</p>



<p>I can’t say that I envy those at the top in the restaurant business. Drinking is just one of the problems that is common as the stress can be very high. One mistake by one of the staff can cost the restaurant in the millions. And, now, more restaurants are struggling than ever, as are other businesses, especially the small ones.</p>



<p>At the same time, soup kitchens and food pantries are in greater demand in many places. Even schools are starting to send food to homes where children are not attending classes while the need for meals still exists.</p>



<p>Chef is just a fancy word for chief: the one in charge. In a lot of jobs you will find that there are too many chiefs and not enough Indians. That’s because we forget that being in charge means serving others, and not about getting our own way. That’s what I miss about being in the soup kitchen: serving others.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://llgt.cafe/serving-others/feed</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Making a Positive Difference</title>
		<link>https://llgt.cafe/making-a-positive-difference</link>
					<comments>https://llgt.cafe/making-a-positive-difference#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[llgt]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 05 Apr 2023 16:45:01 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Career]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Question]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[LLGT]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://llgt.cafe/?p=684</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[If you could choose any career where you could make the most difference, what would you choose? It’s not as if there are any jobs that don’t make a difference in the lives of others — from doctors to trash collectors — but there are&#160;<a class="read-more" href="https://llgt.cafe/making-a-positive-difference">&#8230;</a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>If you could choose any career where you could make the most difference, what would you choose? It’s not as if there are any jobs that don’t make a difference in the lives of others — from doctors to trash collectors — but there are some that seemingly make a greater difference. Which one might you choose?</p>



<p>Teaching is one career that has the potential to impact a number of people. It can be a positive impact, but teachers can also have a negative impact on some of their students. Not everyone learns the same and not every teacher can reach every student, but the potential to reach students, to impact their lives well into the future is still great.</p>



<p>Someone in the medical field also may have a chance to impact the lives of others, whether shot tor long term. It’s a demanding job that may pay well, but can bring with it a great deal of stress. It’s a hard job to stay with long term but can have its rewards as well as its drawbacks. And it’s easy to get into debt to complete one’s education.</p>



<p>Journalists have the opportunity to tell stories: to let others know what is happening in the world around them. Its the rare story that makes a real impact in the lives of others, and many stories go unread by the masses, but there is still that chance to break that story or share that truth that could make a difference.</p>



<p>Law enforcement have a job that I don’t envy. Their job is to fix things when they go wrong and to find criminals. We know what happens when things go wrong: the wrong person is arrested or the innocent is killed. But there are times when people’s lives are saved, people are protected, and there are times when justice is served.</p>



<p>Inventors have an opportunity to change the future. Usually, those who invent don’t work alone but work for a larger company or alongside others who help them. It takes people with an inventive mind to create better transportation, easier ways to do things and new ways to save lives. There is almost no limit to want inventors can come up with.</p>



<p>Athletes have a unique opportunity. Those who make it to the professional level can not only make better than average salaries, but they can use their notoriety to help others: raising funds to help those in need, visiting children and their families in hospitals, and just encouraging young people to go further.</p>



<p>Politicians can have a major impact on a countries future. We tend to think of today’s politicians as crooks, seeking only after their own interests, but there are good politicians out there, making a positive difference, going against the crowd to help others.</p>



<p>I would love to find a way to help children. I once had the idea to put together a photo book to sell and raise money to help these homeless children, but nothing ever came of it. What would you do? Maybe you are already making a positive impact on the lives of those around you. One of the places that we can make the biggest difference is in the home. It cannot be understated the difference that a mother, a father or a guardian can have on children, and it can’t be underestimated the power that families have on a nation. We can make a positive change or we can make a negative one. Which would you choose?</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://llgt.cafe/making-a-positive-difference/feed</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Travel While You Work</title>
		<link>https://llgt.cafe/travel-while-you-work</link>
					<comments>https://llgt.cafe/travel-while-you-work#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[llgt]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 17 Mar 2023 14:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Career]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Making Money]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Travel]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[LLGT]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://llgt.cafe/?p=602</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[If you are thinking about picking up and traveling, whether you plan on spending the year traveling around your area or you plan on spending some time in another country, there are more options now then there were just twenty or thirty years ago. Internet&#160;<a class="read-more" href="https://llgt.cafe/travel-while-you-work">&#8230;</a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>If you are thinking about picking up and traveling, whether you plan on spending the year traveling around your area or you plan on spending some time in another country, there are more options now then there were just twenty or thirty years ago. Internet and high speed communication has not only allowed people in places outside of the United States to do jobs that once had to be done domestically but also allow people to take many jobs wherever they want.</p>



<p>You may not need a computer for this first one, though many restaurants use computers these days to keep track of their inventory. When I went into the military, I wanted something that I could use when I got out. I wasn’t interested in being a mechanic or learning something that might be so specialized that it would be of no use when I got out. Maybe you’ve heard of the degree in underwater basket weaving. It’s one of those jobs that it’s hard to find in the market place. Or maybe a degree in general studies.</p>



<p>It turned out that what I learned about cooking was only a small part of my culinary education. It did, however, lead to most of my international travel but certainly not most of my domestic travel.</p>



<p>Photography is another thing that I would like to do. I’ve been able to take pictures wherever I go, but I’ve never been able to do it professionally. The amount of money that I’ve made over the years likely wouldn’t pay even a month’s worth of rent, now. Yet there are wedding photographers, photojournalists and photographers who make YouTube videos who are able to travel to different parts of the world and make at least enough money to live off of.</p>



<p>One of my friends in Spokane had a business promoting concerts. This job took him over a wide area of the United States, with offices in at least a few states and at least a few hundred employees.</p>



<p>I have another friend who is a doctor. I’m not sure whether or not he travels, but I know that there are doctors who travel on missions trips, often offering free services in areas where medical help may be harder to find. There are even huge ships dedicated to helping people in these areas, all paid for by donations and run mostly by volunteers.</p>



<p>Speaking of volunteering, I knew someone who was planing to go to Hawaii to work on an organic farm. This work was volunteer work, but I guess he had enough money saved up that it wasn’t an issue for him. Some of the students from the culinary school where I attended went to places like New York City to work for top chefs on television programs, not for any money but for the ability to be able to put it on their resume and for the money that they might be able to make later in their careers.</p>



<p>If you can get your own television show, that may allow you to travel. Being in movies might do the same, though more and more movies these days do their travel virtually these days. If you can’t get a studio to pay your way, maybe YouTube or some other form of social media will.</p>



<p>If you can do well enough on Amazon, selling your products online or making money through affiliate marketing, then you should be able to pay your own way. I found one family on YouTube, The Kelley Krew, that was able to take to the road with a family of six, now seven, and spend that year in a large travel RV and truck.</p>



<p>There are other jobs as well that will allow you to travel, whether you are working for someone else or working independently: whether you require $100 thousand or more to get through the year or just a few hundred a month to get by. it’s all up to you. And, of course, local restrictions on travel.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
